Date: Wed, 15 Sep 1999 03:23:41 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: News media, 15 Sep 1999

An outbreak of malaria and Japanese encephalitis has killed 120 people over
the past month in areas along the India-Nepal border, a senior health
official in the northern state of Uttar Pradesh said on Wednesday.
V. K. Dewan, state principal secretary for medical and health issues, said
that 32 people were killed by malaria in the eastern district of Bahraich
over the past week alone. He said that medicines and insecticides had been
rushed to the affected areas, and the World Health Organisation and the
U.N. Children's fund had sent teams to the affected areas to assist state
health department officials.

"Adequate measures are being taken to contain the disease before they take
the form of an epidemic," Dewan said.
--
